div.p: Modifiers are arbitrary functions used to compute state from original data coming from Hive blockchain and Ceramic for example. Such a modifier for checking against a blocklist where the offending records can be removed from the database. Another example is using a modifier to see how many views a video post got, then only caching the most highly viewed video records in memory for maximum performance

div.p: The graph engine is intended to go out and find the parent-child relationships of datasets. For example a blog post may have multiple comments related to it. Those comments might be located on a different network than the original. The original post existing on Hive blockchain then comments being posted on Ceramic. The graph engine is meant to go out and find related database then create an index of the relationship between the two posts (parent post, and child post)
This indexing process is heavily coupled with the P2P aspect for locating and finding related datasets. However, this will be addressed in a separate section

Aside from announcing a dataset to the network, an indexer can index datasets using discovery engines such as searching through a blockchain or indexing an RSS feed. RSS feed is unlikely to be implemented due to the insecure nature of them in general, but it would effectively retrieve the feed, then process each individual post.

h1.span: The dataset identifier is to the indexer node. For Ceramic documents this would be Ceramic://k2****. For social media posts on Ceramic the identifier would likely be an extension of the IDX ID. For example did:3:<Really long crypto number>/social-media-post-1. From there the indexer node can resolve the DID, lookup the post permlink, then retrieve the post content from the ceramic doc. For hive this would be a lot simpler, simply looking up the content from a Hive RPC endpoint... Once the content of the post has been retrieved, it can be processed and indexed accordingly. This does not guarantee the post will be indexed. The post must be checked against the schema(s) supported and required by the indexer node. For SPK network we will have our own set of schemas to support posts on the network. If the post does not validate any of the schemas, it will be discarded.

To get around this issue Ceramic documents can be updated, and posted via the Ceramic HTTP API and a SPK network custom API to a remote node.

span.font: Are nodes that take the responsibility of keeping track of the graph index of a particular dataset, and the dataset's children. These custodian nodes announce to the network what documents they are responsible for. Other nodes on the network will store records of all known custodian nodes. Non custodian nodes forward complex queries, ask for indexes and announce children to the custodian entity. These custodian nodes will keep track of other custodian nodes interested in the same dataset. This will allow allow custodian nodes of the same dataset to keep their indexes in sync.

div.style: font-size: 13px
div.span: Part of the problem with a distributed document indexing layer is the inability to keep track of completely separate, but related pieces of data. The custodian nodes fix this by turning completely separate

datasets into an abridged graph index representing the relationships between each dataset. To do this the custodian node must first identify child documents of a root document. This would be accomplished by remote nodes forwarding documents to the custodian node. Once the custodian node has received a document it will pull then validate the document of authenticity/ensure it matches the required schema. Once the validation check has passed, the custodian node will add the dataset to the local graph index, then announce the child leaf to other known custodian nodes. Custodian nodes will also do validation of announcements from other custodian to ensure absolutely no erroneous data enters into the graph index. Custodian nodes might have different policies for what to allow into the index or not, so this model must allow for conflict free operations and no uniform or centralizing model should be used.
Another point of the custodian nodes is to isolate and create a super highway for where graph indexes are stored. Ideally, this leads to greater scalability and significant performance improvements.

div.p: One of the issues with the approach being discussed is the possibility that child datasets could be cutoff or not mentioned in the graph index for the reason of them being too deep in the graph. Additionally, this also brings up the issue of spam. If there are too many roots being announced then there is a high rate of bloat vs only a single root. To put this into context imagine the following scenario... A youtube video exists with 2000 comments. The youtube video is the root post. The top comment of the youtube video has over 300 subcomments (children of children). The problem is those 300 comments are not immediately indexed from the root element, but rather the top comment. Inorder to get the 300 comments you must query a graph index dedicated for the top comment. In most cases this would be fine as the custodian for the root element would need to index everything down the lowest leaf. However, in more practical cases we should assume the top comment has an entirely separate custodian. The issue is with potentially 10-100x more roots being announced to the network, it could add significant overhead to the amount of data that needs to be stored into the graph index..

Conclusion/notes: For the time being this should be a point of investigation and not as a definite scalability issue. The system at hand is already many factors more scalable than Hive blockchain or other unified database.

div.h1: Complex queries vs graph index queries
div.p: Complex queries are very similar in definition to database queries in MySql or mongodb. Due to this reason it's hard and in some cases impossible to execute complex queries in a fully distributed indexing system such as the one being architected here. For complex queries to be possible a full indexing node must be operated which aims to index nearly the entire visible network in full detail (all metadata with no exceptions). The full indexing node will be able to handle complex queries. In the future we are hoping to divide complex queries into multiple full indexing nodes or partial indexing nodes to attempt to further decentralize the more complicate parts of indexing the network

Graph indexes are specifically meant for indexing the parent-child relationships of datasets. This index allows us to search for the child comments of a post in a quick and effective fashion while retaining the decentralized nature of the project and with minimal impact.

div.p: One of the problems with storing data on a distributed or decentralized network is the potential for significant delay when retrieving a piece of information. Or worse, never receive it. To solve the architecture must be designed in a way to withstand delays. In the case of the SPK network indexing layer this is crucial. For both P2P systems and the backend infrastructure as well as the user experience.

Example case: The indexing system allows for indexing a subgraph of a parent root. Some entries in the subgraph might take a significant amount of time to retrieve if they are not cached. In this case the entries that are cached will be returned instantly. The entries that are not cached will be added to a retrieval queue. Once the delayed entries have been retrieved they can be streamed back to the client through an async iterable or return the updated results next time the subgraph is queried.

div.p: For applications developers to utilize the SPK network for their own applications. We must provide a way for multiple different type of datasets to exist in the same subgraph at any given time. For example comments vs upvotes/downvotes. Those two things are completely separate operations, yet attached to the same parent post. To accomplish this we must provide a way to filter, and categorize datasets by their relevant schema. The below diagram describes the flow between the graph index and the schema registry.

Later down the road more tight integration can be formed such as doing dynamic validation (outside of typing) that checks for specific dynamic conditions in order for the dataset to be valid. Additionally, 3rd party applications can trigger a specific event when the subgraph entries are processed.
